While content analyses of manifestos and televised debates are important, there are two limitations to these indicators. First, parties can communicate with voters through other forums as well (Naurin, 2009). Second, our analysis covers explicitly expressed issue messages. Obviously parties sometimes use more implicit ways to communicate their positions (Federico, 2004; Gilens, 1999). To gain a more complete picture, we turn to voters' perceptions of parties' campaign issues as captured by an open-ended question in the SNES voter studies. More specifically, respondents are asked about what issues each party has emphasized the most during the campaign (Oscarsson and Holmberg, 2008: 52). Figure 5
 displays the highest proportion of respondents who perceived that immigration was a prime issue for any established party (see also Table 4
). As before, the environment issue and the main issue are included as points of reference.
